         <abstract>
            <p>On October 19, 1987, NYSE stocks in the S&amp;P index declined seven percentage points more than NYSE stocks not in this index. In the first hour of trading on October 20, the S&amp;P stocks virtually recovered to the level of the non-S&amp;P stocks. There is a strong relation between order imbalances and stock price movements, both in analyses of time series and cross-sections. Thus, in addition to the breakdown in the linkage between future prices and the spot index on these two days, there were also breakdowns in the linkage among NYSE stocks.</p>
         </abstract>
